title: ArcGIS Server Service State and Usage Statistics
agents: special
catalog: app/arcgis
license: GPL
distribution: check_mk
description:
 Monitors the configured and realtime state of individual ArcGIS Server
 services published on federated ArcGIS Server instances, and optionally
 their usage statistics over a rolling time window.

 The state check compares the service's configured state (the intended
 state set by an administrator) against its realtime state (what the
 server actually reports). A service configured as STARTED but not
 running produces a CRIT result by default. A service intentionally
 stopped (configured STOPPED, realtime STOPPED) produces OK by default.
 Services in transitional states such as STARTING or STOPPING produce
 WARN by default.

 When the {arcgis_service_stats} section is also present - which requires
 the service statistics collection to be enabled in the special agent rule
 and usage reports to be enabled on the ArcGIS Server site - the check
 additionally reports per-service usage metrics for the configured time
 window (default: last hour). All metrics are aggregated from the
 ArcGIS Server Usage Reports API and represent the rolling window, not a
 point-in-time snapshot.

 The following usage metrics are collected when available:

 {Request count} - Total number of requests received in the window.

 {Requests per second} - Average request rate over the window. With the
 default LAST_HOUR window this reflects recent load closely.

 {Failed requests / Failure rate} - Count and percentage of requests that
 returned a failure response. Alert thresholds for failure rate are
 configurable.

 {Timed-out requests / Timeout rate} - Count and percentage of requests
 that exceeded the server-side timeout. Alert thresholds are configurable.

 {Average response time} - Mean response time in milliseconds across all
 non-null time slices in the window. Optional warn/crit thresholds can be
 configured per service.

 {Maximum response time} - Highest response time recorded in any time
 slice of the window.

 {Average wait time} - Mean time in milliseconds that requests spent
 waiting for a free service instance. Only non-zero when the instance
 pool was saturated and requests queued.

 {Maximum wait time} - Highest wait time recorded in any time slice.

 {Max running instances} - Peak number of ArcSOC instances that were
 active simultaneously during the window. Equivalent to the "Instance
 Used" metric in ArcGIS Monitor dashboards.

 Service data is piggybacked to the host representing each federated
 ArcGIS Server. The piggyback host name is the server name as returned
 by the Portal federation API, lowercased. Usage statistics are
 collected in a separate agent section with a configurable cache interval
 (default: 300 seconds) to avoid creating usage reports on every check
 cycle.

 This check requires ArcGIS Enterprise 11.1 or later. The
 ServiceRunningInstancesMax metric requires ArcGIS Enterprise 11.1+
 to be combined with request metrics in a single usage report.

item:
 The full path of the ArcGIS service including folder and service type,
 matching the format returned by the ArcGIS Server services report API.
 Root-level services appear as {ServiceName.ServiceType}, for example
 {Utilities.PrintingTools.GPServer}. Services in folders appear as
 {FolderName/ServiceName.ServiceType}, for example
 {BaseMap/Address.MapServer}.

discovery:
 One service is created for each published ArcGIS service discovered
 via the ArcGIS Server REST Admin API during agent collection. System
 services under the System and Utilities folders are included. Services
 can be filtered at collection time using the server include/exclude
 regex options in the special agent rule.